Hmm, I see what you&#39;re doing here, in order to have white and black squares alternate, but it does make your next job (working out which square you&#39;re currently outputting HTML for) extremely difficult.

You&#39;re better off doing a nested `for` loop, each with 8 iterations; the outer one for rows, and the inner one for squares in each row.

Doing a nested `for` loop might seem more complicated to the beginner, but it&#39;s actually a much more accurate representation of what a chessboard looks like - an 8x8 grid - which then makes it much easier to think about.

Another great example of using a nested `for` loop, which is almost exactly the approach you should be taking here, have a look at this example where a 10x10 multiplication square is output: https://www.w3resource.com/php-exercises/php-for-loop-exercise-10.php

You can use the modulus (`%`) operator to decide whether to make the square black or white.

    for ($i=0; $i&lt;10; $i++) {
        echo $i % 2;
    }
    // Will output 01010101...
    // ... so if 0 is white and 1 is black...

You&#39;ll have to add the value of the current row AND the current square, and then use the modulus operator, to differ the position of black/white squares on each row.

Then, for doing something special with your B4  square, it&#39;s just a case of a simple `if` expression:

    if ($row == 2 &amp;&amp; $square == 4) {
        // Output chess piece HTML
    }

(In this case I&#39;ve assumed you&#39;ve started the loop iterations at 1, but it&#39;s more common in PHP and other languages to see loops starting at 0 because that&#39;s how array structures are numbered. And of course, row B here, the second row, is row 2.)

As I can see you&#39;re learning, I&#39;ve not spelled out the answer for you here, but you and others should hopefully find this helpful.

